# In Exact-Support Audits Check Mirror-Cross Pairs Before Self-Pair Distractions

When an exact-support audit uses mandatory conjugate completion, inspect the
distinct mirror-cross pairs on the mirror-complete ledger before spending time
on self-pairs or on the visually intended seed orbit.

Those mirror-cross pairs are often the first honest spill mechanism.
If the audit only checks the tidy intended orbit, it will understate the true
closure burden and may mistake a truncated picture for an exact survivor.

A vanished self-pair doubling term does not rescue the budget.
It only means the real failure mechanism lies in distinct off-orbit pairings
that the exact closure rule already requires.

